Part 1: Non-Technical (General User Experience)
These focus on how the site feels and if it meets the needs of a local shopper.

Can you find the "About" page from the home screen in less than three seconds?

Is the contrast between the green background and white text easy for you to read?

When you add an item to the cart, is the "Success" message clear enough?

Does the "Order" page look organized, or are there too many products on the screen at once?

Is it clear that you have to be logged in before you can see your order history?

Are the images of the farm produce high-quality enough to make you want to buy them?

If you were a producer, would you find the "Stock Management" table easy to understand?

Does the "Delivery" vs "Collection" choice on the checkout page make sense to you?

Is the "Loyalty Points" reward explained well enough to encourage you to buy more?

Are the buttons (Login, Register, Update) big enough to click easily on a mobile phone?

Is the contact information easy to find if you have a problem with an order?

Does the website feel like a "local hub," or does it feel like a generic online shop?

If you forgot your password, is there a clear way to get help on the login page?

Does the "Cart" page show you a clear breakdown of the price before you pay?

When you click "About," do the different farm descriptions help you trust the food quality?

Part 2: Technical (Database & System Integrity)
These are for the technical audience who can check the database to see if the site is working correctly.

Look at the users table: Are the passwords stored as long scrambled strings (hashed) or can you read them?

In the orders table: Does the total_price column correctly include the £2.50 fee when "Delivery" is chosen?

Check the products table: When a producer updates a stock level on the website, does the number change instantly in the database?

Look at the users table after a purchase: Did the points column increase by the correct amount (1 point per £1 spent, rounded down)?

In the orders table: Are the items listed as a single readable string (e.g., "Apple (x2), Steak (x1)")?

Does the order_date column in the database record the exact time the "Complete Purchase" button was clicked?

Look at the products table: If a new producer registers, are all 13 default items (wheat, honey, etc.) automatically added for them with 0 stock?

If you try to register a second user with a username that already exists in the database, does the website stop you?

Check the users table: Is there a specific column that correctly identifies if a person is a "customer" or a "producer"?

In the orders table: Is the username linked correctly to the person who actually made the purchase?

Does the checkout form prevent you from moving forward if the "Card Number" box has fewer than 12 digits?

When a producer changes a stock level to a negative number, does the database allow it or does the website block it?

Look at the orders table: Is the "Delivery Method" saved exactly as it was selected on the form?

After clicking "Logout," if you try to use the "Back" button in the browser, does the database session stay closed?

Does the total_price in the database use a format that allows for pence (like 10.50) or is it only whole numbers?
